\
\f1\b\fs28\li2200 selector:dispatch:args:\f0\b0\
\f0\fs28\li2500 +{\b selector}:(SEL){\i s}{\b dispatch}:(ARGIMP){\i d}{\b args}:(void *){\i a}\fs16\
\
\f0\fs28\li2200 Creates a Message instance with the indicated selector name and pointer to argument structure.  The argument structure for a message consists of return value of the method (if not void), followed by the arguments of the method :\fs16\
\
\f2\fs24\li2800 struct \{\
  int ret;\
  int a;\
  double d;\
\}\
\f0\fs16\
\f0\fs28\li2200 The above structure corresponds to a method such as (int)foo:(int)a bar:(double)d.\fs16\
\
\f0\fs28\li2200 The {\i dispatch} argument is a (compiler generated) function that decodes the arguments from the argument structure, and dispatches the messages.\fs16\
\
\fs16\
\
\f1\b\fs28\li2200 selector\f0\b0\
\f0\fs28\li2500 - (SEL){\b selector}\fs16\
\
\f0\fs28\li2200 Returns the selector for this message.\fs16\
\
\fs16\
\
\f1\b\fs28\li2200 sentTo:\f0\b0\
\f0\fs28\li2500 -{\b sentTo}:{\i receiver}\fs16\
\
\f0\fs28\li2200 Forwards the message to {\i receiver} (if it's not {\b nil}) and returns the message itself ({\i self}), not the return value of the message that was forwarded to {\i receiver}.  The latter return value is associated to the Message instance, so that it can be returned to the sender of the message that caused a {\f2 doesNotUnderstand:} message to be sent.\fs16\
